  "summary": "Rolly (Rowley) Claude discusses the identity of a deceased man with Hercule Poirot. Rolly expresses distrust toward Rosaline Clude, noting that if the dead man were André Guerin, Rosaline would have no financial motive to deny knowing him. Rolly asks Poirot to find someone who can definitively identify the body, as Guerin had no living relatives in England. Poirot uses his precise memory to recall a name from a previous encounter at a club: Captain Porter. After sending a note through his servant George to the Garter Club, Poirot arranges a meeting with Colonel Porter for that afternoon.\n\nPoirot and Rolly meet Colonel Porter at his dilapidated home on Cromwell Road. Poirot observes that the Colonel appears to be in financial distress, noting the absence of a valuable carpet that had been recently removed. During the meeting, Poirot shows the Colonel a newspaper photograph of the deceased, identified in the press as Enock Yate. Upon inspecting the photo, Colonel Porter emphatically identifies the man as Robert Andrei.\n\nLater, Rolly calls Lynn to invite her to Rolly's Grove, claiming to have good news. When Lynn arrives at the field, Rolly tells her that they are \"on a roll\" and mentions that he has been working with Hercule Poirot, whom they had previously heard of during the war.",
